{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502883","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502883"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:51:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:51:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1909"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1909"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.48,0.05,0.09,0.26,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1909"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95717"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1909"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1909"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78518"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"951"},{"type":"tags","id":"1164"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"3310"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12691"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14481"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30250"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36659"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95717"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day gradual history of weakness on the left side of her face and the inability to completely close her left eye. She is otherwise in good health and does not have any significant medical history. She does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a visible droop to her left side facial muscles, difficultly raising her eyebrows on the left side and failure of closure of the left eye when asked. The rest of the physical examination is normal and there are no signs of any other neurological deficits or fatigability.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No investigations required","Nerve conduction studies","Full blood count and ESR","CT brain","MRI brain"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute onset of unilateral, lower motor neuron weakness of the facial nerve in the absence of an identifiable cause (otherwise known as Bell\u0027s palsy), the most common cause of cranial neuropathies. Bell\u0027s palsy is most often associated with herpes simplex or varicella zoster virus reactivation of the facial nerve. Less commonly, facial nerve palsy may be secondary to other causes of central or peripheral facial nerve palsy such as strokes, cutaneous cancers of the face and neck or trauma. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBell\u0027s palsy is a clinical diagnosis differentiated from other causes of facial nerve palsy through careful neurological examination. In ischaemic stroke (central nervous system pathology) there is typically sparing of forehead involvement as the facial nerve receives motor innervation from both hemispheres of the cerebral cortex. Therefore an ischaemic stroke (unilateral pathology) would only result in paralysis of the lower half of the face due to the continued motor innervation of the forehead from the unaffected contralateral cerebral cortex motor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the absence of any suspicious features (diplopia, dysphagia, dizziness) from the clinical assessment, \u003Cstrong\u003Eno investigations\u003C/strong\u003E at this stage are going to influence either the diagnosis or the management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMost cases of Bell\u0027s palsy will resolve spontaneously, with the recovery period usually becoming apparent within three weeks of the onset of the symptoms. Recovery may take up to two months, and if there has been no sign of recovery after six weeks, various investigations may be appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe initial management of Bell\u0027s palsy focuses on eye protection (artificial tears, eye patch or tape at night, sunglasses when outdoors) and supportive care. Corticosteroids started within 72 hours of symptom onset may improve outcomes. Antiviral therapy (e.g., acyclovir) may also be considered in combination with corticosteroids, although its benefit is less clear.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENerve conduction studies\u003C/strong\u003E are not routinely performed in the initial assessment of Bell\u0027s palsy. They may be considered if there is no improvement after several weeks to assess the extent of nerve damage and prognosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Efull blood count and ESR\u003C/strong\u003E would not be specifically helpful in diagnosing or managing Bell\u0027s palsy. These tests might be considered if there was suspicion of a systemic inflammatory condition, which is not evident in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT brain\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI brain\u003C/strong\u003E imaging studies might be considered if there are other associated physical findings or if the facial nerve palsy is progressive and unremitting. In this case, the presentation is typical for Bell\u0027s palsy, and there are no red flags to suggest central nervous system involvement.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most cases of Bell\u0027s palsy will resolve spontaneously and no therapeutic intervention is going to influence the outcome if the symptoms have been present for more than three days.","In peripheral lesions, the patient is unable to raise their eyebrows on the affected side."],"references":["Holland NJ, Bernstein JM. Bell\u0027s palsy. BMJ Clin Evid 2014; 04:1204-20.","Wallwork B, Panizza B, Phan N. \u0027A general practice approach to Bell\u0027s palsy\u0027. Australian Family Physician. November : (11). Accessed July 2024. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2016/november/a-general-practice-approach-to-bell-s-palsy#:~:text=Sparing%20of%20forehead%20movement%20may,single%20branch%20of%20the%20nerve."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78518"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1909"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78518","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78518"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-29T09:25:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-29T09:26:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1909"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95717"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","